{"runId":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro@2026-05-14T01-44-25-815Z","slug":"your-foreign-keys-are-killing-performance","locale":"ar","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","modelPath":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-14T01:44:35.256Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2025-12-29--your-foreign-keys-are-killing-performance/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2025-12-29--your-foreign-keys-are-killing-performance/ar/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/your-foreign-keys-are-killing-performance/ar/openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro/2026-05-14T01-44-25-815Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"710eef136b3fb20edb779995cdd3e6132250ff49ebbe95c2159902711bea426c","outputHash":"93260e03a5b383ea88c196d59aa63040a40b7d775389fac1b0318d00c6e813d7","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"**Summary**  \nThe article argues that the debate over foreign‑key (FK) performance is misplaced: the real decision is which failure mode you can tolerate, not “fast vs. correct.” It uses a weather‑monitoring example and a cautionary story of a system that removed all FKs, ending up with billions of orphaned rows, to show that constraints provide essential data‑integrity guarantees that outweigh their modest write‑time cost. When ultra‑fast inserts are truly required, the author suggests concrete mitigations—lower isolation levels, batch commits, or redesigning the schema as an append‑only log with JSONB—rather than discarding FKs outright. The piece also critiques the textbook‑style push for strict normalization, warning that snapshot data (e.g., historical orders, audit logs) should often be denormalized at write time.  \n\n**Intended audience**: Web developers, backend engineers, and database designers who wrestle with schema design and performance trade‑offs.  \n\n**Tone & framing**: A pragmatic, slightly rant‑like analysis that mixes technical advice with everyday metaphors (safety glass, seatbelts) to stress that constraints are safety fea